Note:
Bash/Shell Parser - AST construction for Bash scripts

This file provides complete syntax analysis for Bash shell scripts.
Constructs an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) representing the script structure.

Features:
- Complete Bash grammar support
- Commands and pipelines
- Control structures (if, while, for, case)
- Function definitions
- Variable assignments and expansions
- Compound commands
- Conditional expressions [[ ]]
- Test expressions [ ]
- Arithmetic expressions $(())
- Command and process substitution
- Redirections and file descriptors
- Here documents

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- frontends/bash/bash_lexer.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/bash/bash_lexer.runa" as Lexer

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant AST_SCRIPT as Integer is 1               Note: Top-level script
Constant AST_COMMAND as Integer is 2              Note: Simple command
Constant AST_PIPELINE as Integer is 3             Note: Pipeline (cmd1 | cmd2)
Constant AST_LIST as Integer is 4                 Note: Command list (&&, ||, ;, &)
Constant AST_COMPOUND_COMMAND as Integer is 5     Note: { commands; }
Constant AST_SUBSHELL as Integer is 6             Note: ( commands )
Constant AST_IF_STATEMENT as Integer is 10        Note: if-then-else-fi
Constant AST_WHILE_STATEMENT as Integer is 11     Note: while-do-done
Constant AST_UNTIL_STATEMENT as Integer is 12     Note: until-do-done
Constant AST_FOR_STATEMENT as Integer is 13       Note: for-do-done
Constant AST_CASE_STATEMENT as Integer is 14      Note: case-in-esac
Constant AST_SELECT_STATEMENT as Integer is 15    Note: select-do-done
Constant AST_FUNCTION_DEFINITION as Integer is 20 Note: function name { }
Constant AST_VARIABLE_ASSIGNMENT as Integer is 21 Note: var=value
Constant AST_VARIABLE as Integer is 22            Note: $var or ${var}
Constant AST_SPECIAL_VARIABLE as Integer is 23    Note: $?, $@, etc.
Constant AST_ARITHMETIC_EXPANSION as Integer is 24 Note: $(())
Constant AST_PARAMETER_EXPANSION as Integer is 25 Note: ${var:-default}
Constant AST_COMMAND_SUBSTITUTION as Integer is 26 Note: $() or ``
Constant AST_PROCESS_SUBSTITUTION as Integer is 27 Note: <() or >()
Constant AST_CONDITIONAL_EXPRESSION as Integer is 30 Note: [[ expression ]]
Constant AST_TEST_EXPRESSION as Integer is 31     Note: [ expression ] or test
Constant AST_ARITHMETIC_EXPRESSION as Integer is 32 Note: (( expression ))
Constant AST_BINARY_EXPRESSION as Integer is 33   Note: Binary operation
Constant AST_UNARY_EXPRESSION as Integer is 34    Note: Unary operation
Constant AST_REDIRECTION as Integer is 40         Note: Input/output redirection
Constant AST_HERE_DOCUMENT as Integer is 41       Note: shifted left by EOF
Constant AST_ARGUMENT as Integer is 50            Note: Command argument
Constant AST_WORD as Integer is 51                Note: Simple word
Constant AST_STRING as Integer is 52              Note: String literal
Constant AST_NUMBER as Integer is 53              Note: Numeric literal
Constant AST_CASE_ITEM as Integer is 60           Note: Case pattern item
Constant AST_PATTERN as Integer is 61             Note: Case pattern

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single uniform AST node type for all Bash grammar productions so the
parser can produce and walk trees with a homogeneous representation; the
node_type constant disambiguates which production yielded the node, and
children/child_count/child_capacity implement a dynamic vector so any
production can have any number of subnodes (Bash case items, command
arguments, redirections, etc.) without separate per-production storage.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
56-byte record (AST_NODE_SIZE) laid out as:
- node_type @0 (8 bytes) - AST_* constant
- value @8 - pointer to associated string, e.g. command name or word text
- line @16, column @24 - source location for diagnostics
- children @32 - pointer to a heap array of child node pointers
- child_count @40 - active child count
- child_capacity @48 - allocated slot count (grown 2x on overflow)
Field offsets are hand-managed via memory_set_int64; add_child handles the
growth invariant child_count <= child_capacity.
@End Implementation
Type called "ASTNode":
    node_type as Integer       Note: AST node type constant
    value as Integer           Note: Node value (string pointer)
    line as Integer            Note: Source line number
    column as Integer          Note: Source column number
    children as Integer        Note: Pointer to children array
    child_count as Integer     Note: Number of children
    child_capacity as Integer  Note: Capacity of children array
End Type

Constant AST_NODE_SIZE as Integer is 56  Note: 7 fields × 8 bytes
Constant INITIAL_CHILD_CAPACITY as Integer is 4

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Minimal recursive-descent parser state: a reference to the streaming
lexer, a one-token lookahead buffer (current_token), and a sticky error
flag. Bash's grammar is mostly LL(1) once command-vs-assignment is
disambiguated by character lookahead inside parse_command, so a single
token of structured lookahead suffices.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
24-byte record (PARSER_SIZE) laid out as:
- lexer @0 - pointer to the BashLexer producing tokens
- current_token @8 - currently-buffered token from the lexer
- has_error @16 - 0 / 1 sticky error indicator set by expect()
create_parser primes current_token with the first lexer token; advance()
destroys the prior token and replaces it.
@End Implementation
Type called "BashParser":
    lexer as Integer           Note: Bash lexer
    current_token as Integer   Note: Current token
    has_error as Integer       Note: Error flag
End Type

Constant PARSER_SIZE as Integer is 24  Note: 3 fields × 8 bytes

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Operations
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
AST node allocation is centralized so all 56-byte record initializations
zero every field. Without zero-init, a freshly-created node could be
treated as having children (non-zero children pointer) by add_child, which
would dereference uninitialized memory.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates AST_NODE_SIZE (56) bytes via Layout.allocate. On allocation
failure returns 0 so callers can short-circuit. Stores node_type @0 and
explicitly zeroes value @8, line @16, column @24, children @32,
child_count @40, child_capacity @48. Returns the node pointer.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_ast_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create AST node with given type

    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with AST_NODE_SIZE

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0   Note: value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0  Note: line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0  Note: column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0  Note: children
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0  Note: child_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, 0  Note: child_capacity

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Null-safe field setter so productions that conditionally attach a value
(e.g. function names, variable identifiers) don't need to check the node
pointer themselves before storing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 immediately if node is 0 (no-op for null nodes). Otherwise
stores value at offset 8 (value field) via memory_set_int64. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "set_node_value" takes node as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set node value

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, value

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Attaches source coordinates to a node so downstream HIR translation and
diagnostic emission can point at the originating Bash source position.
Kept as a separate process from value-setting because not every node has
useful location data attached (e.g. synthesized nodes).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 if node is 0. Otherwise writes line to offset 16 and column to
offset 24 via memory_set_int64. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "set_node_location" takes node as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set node source location

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, column

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Implements dynamic-vector growth for ASTNode.children with a doubling
strategy: amortized O(1) appends across all child additions on a single
parent node. Lazy initial allocation (only on first append) avoids the
cost of allocating capacity for the many parser productions that produce
zero-child nodes (literals, empty bodies).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 if either node or child is 0 (refuses to attach a null child or
add to a null parent). Reads child_count @40 and child_capacity @48.
Growth path:
- capacity == 0: allocate INITIAL_CHILD_CAPACITY * 8 bytes, store pointer
  at @32, set capacity to INITIAL_CHILD_CAPACITY.
- count >= capacity: double the capacity, allocate new array, manually
  copy each of the count slots from the old array (read at i*8, write at
  i*8), deallocate the old array, update pointer and capacity.
Then writes the child pointer at children_array + child_count*8 and
increments child_count.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_child" takes node as Integer, child as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add child to AST node

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If child is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 40
    Let child_capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 48

    Note: Allocate or grow children array
    If child_capacity is equal to 0:
        Let new_capacity be INITIAL_CHILD_CAPACITY
        Let children_array be proc allocate from Layout with new_capacity multiplied by 8

        If children_array is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, children_array
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, new_capacity
        Set child_capacity to new_capacity
    Otherwise:
        If child_count is greater than or equal to child_capacity:
            Set new_capacity to child_capacity multiplied by 2
            Let new_array be proc allocate from Layout with new_capacity multiplied by 8

            If new_array is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            Let old_array be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32

            Let i be 0
            While i is less than child_count:
                Let child_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with old_array, i multiplied by 8
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with new_array, i multiplied by 8, child_ptr
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While

            proc deallocate from Layout with old_array

            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, new_array
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, new_capacity
            Set child_capacity to new_capacity
        End If
    End If

    Set children_array to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with children_array, child_count multiplied by 8, child

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, child_count plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructor that establishes the LL(1) invariant by prefetching the first
token before any production runs. Without prefetch, the first call to
match() or current_token_type() would observe an uninitialized
current_token field and read garbage.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates PARSER_SIZE (24) bytes. On allocation failure returns 0.
Stores the lexer pointer at offset 0, zero at offset 16 (has_error
cleared). Calls next_token on the lexer to grab the first token and
stores it at offset 8 (current_token). Returns the parser pointer.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_parser" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create Bash parser

    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with PARSER_SIZE

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0  Note: has_error

    Note: Get first token
    Let first_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, first_token

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases the parser record and the token it owns. The lexer's lifetime
is owned by the caller (it can outlive the parser to drive a second
pass), so it is not destroyed here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 immediately if parser is 0 (idempotent for null). Reads
current_token at offset 8; if non-zero destroys it via
Lexer.destroy_token to release the token's string allocation. Then
deallocates the parser record via Layout.deallocate. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "destroy_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy parser

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If current_token is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy_token from Lexer with current_token
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Operations
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Returns the type of the lookahead token. Returning TOKEN_EOF when the
current_token slot is empty lets all parser productions treat
end-of-input as a regular sentinel via the existing match-on-EOF paths
rather than requiring an extra null check at every call site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_token at parser offset 8. If 0, returns TOKEN_EOF from the
Lexer module. Otherwise reads the token's node_type at the token's
offset 0 and returns it.
@End Implementation
Process called "current_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token type

    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If current_token is equal to 0:
        Return TOKEN_EOF from Lexer
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 0

    Return token_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Companion of current_token_type that returns the value pointer (typically
a string) attached to the lookahead token. Returns 0 for a missing token
so productions like parse_word can skip value capture cleanly at EOF.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_token at parser offset 8. If 0 returns 0; otherwise reads
the token's value at the token's offset 8 and returns it.
@End Implementation
Process called "current_token_value" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token value

    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If current_token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 8

    Return value
End Process

@Reasoning:
The single point where token consumption happens: it must destroy the
prior token before overwriting current_token to avoid leaking the prior
token's string allocation. Every production that wants to consume the
lookahead routes through here (directly or via match_and_advance /
expect) to keep that invariant centralized.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads lexer (offset 0) and current_token (offset 8). If current_token is
non-zero calls Lexer.destroy_token on it. Calls Lexer.next_token on the
lexer to fetch the next token and stores it at offset 8. Returns the
newly-stored token pointer for callers that want to inspect it without
a separate current_token read.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If current_token is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy_token from Lexer with current_token
    End If

    Let next_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, next_token

    Return next_token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pure lookahead predicate that never advances. Productions use it for
optional-token detection (e.g. checking for an `elif` before committing
to one of two alternatives). Separating non-consuming match from
consuming advance lets the LL(1) decisions stay clean.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_token_type, compares against the supplied token_type.
Returns 1 on equality, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation
Process called "match" takes parser as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches type

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    If current_type is equal to token_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Combines lookahead and optional consumption in one call so productions
that want to consume a token if present (e.g. optional `()` after a
function name, optional list separators) don't have to write the
"match then advance" pattern twice in source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls match. If it returns 1, calls advance and returns 1. Otherwise
returns 0 without consuming anything.
@End Implementation
Process called "match_and_advance" takes parser as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Match token type and advance if matched

    Let matched be proc match with parser, token_type

    If matched is equal to 1:
        proc advance from parser
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Implements the "this token MUST be present" contract for mandatory
grammar elements like `then` after the `if` condition, `done` after a
loop body, etc. On mismatch sets the sticky has_error flag instead of
throwing or returning a special node so the rest of the parse continues
producing a partial tree that callers can still inspect.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls match. On mismatch (0), writes 1 to parser offset 16 (has_error)
and returns 0. On match advances past the token and returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "expect" takes parser as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Expect token type, error if not matched

    Let matched be proc match with parser, token_type

    If matched is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 1  Note: Set error flag
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance from parser

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash uses newlines as statement terminators inside list-of-commands
contexts, but compound constructs (after `then`, `do`, `in`, etc.) accept
any number of blank lines before their body. Centralizing the newline-
swallowing here lets every compound production simply call
skip_newlines after its keywords without writing the loop locally.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Infinite loop that calls match against TOKEN_NEWLINE; breaks immediately
once a non-newline token is current; otherwise calls advance to consume
the newline and continues. Returns 1 unconditionally.
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_newlines" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip any newline tokens

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_newline be proc match with parser, TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer

        If is_newline is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance from parser
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Forward Declarations
Note: ============================================================================


Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
"Word" in Bash grammar collapses several lexical categories (unquoted
words, single/double-quoted strings, numbers, and expansions) into a
single parse-level concept because they are all interchangeable in
command and argument positions. This function dispatches across all of
those token kinds to a small set of AST node types so the rest of the
parser only needs to care about the higher-level distinction.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_token_type and tests each accepted token kind in turn:
- TOKEN_WORD  -> AST_WORD with token value
- TOKEN_STRING, TOKEN_SINGLE_QUOTED_STRING, TOKEN_DOUBLE_QUOTED_STRING ->
  AST_STRING
- TOKEN_NUMBER -> AST_NUMBER
- TOKEN_COMMAND_SUBSTITUTION -> AST_COMMAND_SUBSTITUTION
- TOKEN_ARITHMETIC_EXPANSION -> AST_ARITHMETIC_EXPANSION
- TOKEN_PARAMETER_EXPANSION -> AST_PARAMETER_EXPANSION
For each match: creates the AST node, calls set_node_value with the
token's value string, advances past the token, returns the node.
Returns 0 when no production matches so the caller can probe whether a
word is available without committing.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_word" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse word token

    Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_WORD from Lexer:
        Let value be proc current_token_value from parser
        Let node be proc create_ast_node from AST_WORD
        proc set_node_value with node, value
        proc advance from parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
        Set value to proc current_token_value from parser
        Set node to proc create_ast_node from AST_STRING
        proc set_node_value with node, value
        proc advance from parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SINGLE_QUOTED_STRING from Lexer:
        Set value to proc current_token_value from parser
        Set node to proc create_ast_node from AST_STRING
        proc set_node_value with node, value
        proc advance from parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DOUBLE_QUOTED_STRING from Lexer:
        Set value to proc current_token_value from parser
        Set node to proc create_ast_node from AST_STRING
        proc set_node_value with node, value
        proc advance from parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer:
        Set value to proc current_token_value from parser
        Set node to proc create_ast_node from AST_NUMBER
        proc set_node_value with node, value
        proc advance from parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Command substitution
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMAND_SUBSTITUTION from Lexer:
        Set value to proc current_token_value from parser
        Set node to proc create_ast_node from AST_COMMAND_SUBSTITUTION
        proc set_node_value with node, value
        proc advance from parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Arithmetic expansion
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ARITHMETIC_EXPANSION from Lexer:
        Set value to proc current_token_value from parser
        Set node to proc create_ast_node from AST_ARITHMETIC_EXPANSION
        proc set_node_value with node, value
        proc advance from parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Parameter expansion
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PARAMETER_EXPANSION from Lexer:
        Set value to proc current_token_value from parser
        Set node to proc create_ast_node from AST_PARAMETER_EXPANSION
        proc set_node_value with node, value
        proc advance from parser
        Return node
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Command arguments are a superset of words: in addition to all the
word-accepted forms, they also include `$var` references that come
through as a TOKEN_DOLLAR followed by a TOKEN_WORD. parse_word handles
the common cases and this wrapper adds the dollar-variable case so
parse_simple_command stays simple.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
First delegates to parse_word; if it returns non-zero, returns that
result. Otherwise peeks the current token type. On TOKEN_DOLLAR, advances
past the dollar, reads the following token's value as the variable name,
creates an AST_VARIABLE node with that name, advances past the name
token, returns the node. Returns 0 if neither path produces a node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_argument" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse command argument

    Let node be proc parse_word from parser

    If node is not equal to 0:
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Could be variable expansion or other special forms
    Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DOLLAR from Lexer:
        proc advance from parser
        Let var_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_VARIABLE
        Let var_name be proc current_token_value from parser
        proc set_node_value with var_node, var_name
        proc advance from parser
        Return var_node
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash has eight redirection operators (`<`, `>`, `>>`, `<>`, `>&`, `&>`,
`&>>`, `<&`) that all share the same syntactic shape: operator followed
by a target word or file descriptor. Recognizing them upfront via a flag
rather than eight separate branches keeps the target-parsing logic
single-pathed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the current token type. Sets is_redirect to 1 for any of the eight
redirection tokens (TOKEN_LESS, TOKEN_GREATER, TOKEN_GREATER_GREATER,
TOKEN_LESS_GREATER, TOKEN_GREATER_AMP, TOKEN_AMP_GREATER,
TOKEN_AMP_GREATER_GREATER, TOKEN_LESS_AMP). If 0 returns 0 without
allocating. Otherwise creates an AST_REDIRECTION node, attaches an empty
operator string placeholder (operator type currently inferred elsewhere
from child position), advances past the operator token, parses the
target via parse_argument, adds it as a child, returns the node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_redirection" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse redirection (>, >>, <, etc.)

    Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    Let is_redirect be 0

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LESS from Lexer:
        Set is_redirect to 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GREATER from Lexer:
        Set is_redirect to 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GREATER_GREATER from Lexer:
        Set is_redirect to 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LESS_GREATER from Lexer:
        Set is_redirect to 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GREATER_AMP from Lexer:
        Set is_redirect to 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AMP_GREATER from Lexer:
        Set is_redirect to 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AMP_GREATER_GREATER from Lexer:
        Set is_redirect to 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LESS_AMP from Lexer:
        Set is_redirect to 1
    End If

    If is_redirect is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let redirect_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_REDIRECTION

    Note: Store redirect operator type
    Let operator_str be proc create_string from StringCore with ""
    proc set_node_value with redirect_node, operator_str

    proc advance from parser

    Note: Parse target (filename or file descriptor)
    Let target be proc parse_argument from parser
    proc add_child with redirect_node, target

    Return redirect_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Simple Command Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A simple command is the command name followed by an arbitrary mix of
arguments and redirections, terminated by any of the list/pipeline
separators or end-of-input. Redirections can appear anywhere in the
argument stream (`cmd >out arg1 arg2 2>&1`), so a single loop pulls
whichever production matches the lookahead at each iteration.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates AST_COMMAND node. Parses the leading word via parse_word; if 0,
returns 0 (no command at this position). Adds it as the first child.
Then an infinite loop:
- breaks on any of: TOKEN_NEWLINE, TOKEN_SEMICOLON, TOKEN_PIPE,
  TOKEN_AMP, TOKEN_AMP_AMP, TOKEN_PIPE_PIPE, TOKEN_EOF
- tries parse_redirection; if it returns a node adds it and Continue
- otherwise tries parse_argument; if 0 break, else add it.
Returns the AST_COMMAND with all collected children.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_simple_command" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse simple command (cmd arg1 arg2 ...)

    Let command_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_COMMAND

    Note: Parse command name
    Let cmd_name be proc parse_word from parser

    If cmd_name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc add_child with command_node, cmd_name

    Note: Parse arguments and redirections
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

        Note: Check for end of command
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AMP from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AMP_AMP from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE_PIPE from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Try redirection
        Let redirect be proc parse_redirection from parser

        If redirect is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with command_node, redirect
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Parse argument
        Let arg be proc parse_argument from parser

        If arg is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc add_child with command_node, arg
    End While

    Return command_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pipeline Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A pipeline is `cmd1 | cmd2 | ...` with optional newlines after each
pipe. Single-command pipelines are returned as the bare command (not
wrapped in AST_PIPELINE) so trivial cases stay simple downstream. Only
when at least one `|` is observed does the wrapping happen.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses the first command via parse_simple_command. If 0, returns 0. Then
match-tests for TOKEN_PIPE; if not present, returns the bare first
command. Otherwise creates AST_PIPELINE, adds first_cmd, and loops:
- match_and_advance on TOKEN_PIPE; if 0 break
- skip_newlines after the pipe
- parse_simple_command; if 0 break, else add child.
Returns the pipeline node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_pipeline" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse pipeline (cmd1 | cmd2 | cmd3)

    Let first_cmd be proc parse_simple_command from parser

    If first_cmd is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let is_pipe be proc match with parser, TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer

    If is_pipe is equal to 0:
        Return first_cmd  Note: Not a pipeline, just simple command
    End If

    Let pipeline_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_PIPELINE
    proc add_child with pipeline_node, first_cmd

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_pipe_check be proc match_and_advance with parser, TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer

        If is_pipe_check is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc skip_newlines from parser

        Let next_cmd be proc parse_simple_command from parser

        If next_cmd is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc add_child with pipeline_node, next_cmd
    End While

    Return pipeline_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: List Parsing (&&, ||, ;, &)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A "list" is a sequence of pipelines joined by `&&`, `||`, `;`, or `&`.
Like pipelines, a single-item list is returned as the bare pipeline so
the AST stays flat in the common case. The four operators are treated
uniformly at this level - their semantic differences (short-circuit vs
sequential vs background) are encoded by the operator tokens in the
ordered child stream, not by separate node types.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses first pipeline; on 0 returns 0. Sets is_list_operator if the
current token type is any of TOKEN_AMP_AMP, TOKEN_PIPE_PIPE,
TOKEN_SEMICOLON, TOKEN_AMP. If 0, returns the bare pipeline. Otherwise
creates AST_LIST and adds the first item. Loop:
- re-detect list operator on current token; if not found, break
- advance past the operator (note: the operator token is currently
  consumed without being attached to the AST_LIST; downstream consumers
  infer it positionally for now)
- skip_newlines
- parse_pipeline; if 0 break, else add child.
Returns AST_LIST.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_list" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse command list with &&, ||, ;, &

    Let first_item be proc parse_pipeline from parser

    If first_item is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    Let is_list_operator be 0

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AMP_AMP from Lexer:
        Set is_list_operator to 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE_PIPE from Lexer:
        Set is_list_operator to 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
        Set is_list_operator to 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AMP from Lexer:
        Set is_list_operator to 1
    End If

    If is_list_operator is equal to 0:
        Return first_item  Note: Not a list, just pipeline
    End If

    Let list_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_LIST
    proc add_child with list_node, first_item

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set token_type to proc current_token_type from parser

        Let is_op be 0

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AMP_AMP from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE_PIPE from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AMP from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If

        If is_op is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance from parser
        proc skip_newlines from parser

        Let next_item be proc parse_pipeline from parser

        If next_item is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc add_child with list_node, next_item
    End While

    Return list_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Control Structure Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Bash if statements use `if COND; then BODY [elif COND; then BODY]*
[else BODY] fi`. The AST flattens elif into pairs of (condition, body)
children inserted into the AST_IF_STATEMENT after the initial condition
and then-body so the resulting tree is uniform: children are
[cond, then_body, elif_cond, elif_body, ..., (optional) else_body].
This avoids needing a separate AST_ELIF_CLAUSE node kind.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
expect TOKEN_IF, skip_newlines. Parse condition list, skip newlines,
expect TOKEN_THEN, skip newlines. Parse then_body list. Create
AST_IF_STATEMENT, add condition then then_body as the first two
children. Loop:
- match TOKEN_ELIF: if 1, advance, skip_newlines, parse elif condition,
  skip_newlines, expect TOKEN_THEN, skip_newlines, parse elif_body, add
  both as further children, skip_newlines, Continue.
- match TOKEN_ELSE: if 1, advance, skip_newlines, parse else_body, add
  as final child, skip_newlines.
- Break in all other cases.
expect TOKEN_FI. Return the if node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_if_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse if-then-else-fi statement

    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_IF from Lexer

    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Let condition be proc parse_list from parser

    proc skip_newlines from parser
    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_THEN from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Let then_body be proc parse_list from parser

    Let if_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_IF_STATEMENT
    proc add_child with if_node, condition
    proc add_child with if_node, then_body

    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Note: Check for elif or else
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_elif be proc match with parser, TOKEN_ELIF from Lexer

        If is_elif is equal to 1:
            proc advance from parser
            proc skip_newlines from parser

            Let elif_cond be proc parse_list from parser

            proc skip_newlines from parser
            proc expect with parser, TOKEN_THEN from Lexer
            proc skip_newlines from parser

            Let elif_body be proc parse_list from parser

            proc add_child with if_node, elif_cond
            proc add_child with if_node, elif_body

            proc skip_newlines from parser
            Continue
        End If

        Let is_else be proc match with parser, TOKEN_ELSE from Lexer

        If is_else is equal to 1:
            proc advance from parser
            proc skip_newlines from parser

            Let else_body be proc parse_list from parser
            proc add_child with if_node, else_body

            proc skip_newlines from parser
        End If

        Break
    End While

    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_FI from Lexer

    Return if_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
While-loop grammar is `while COND; do BODY; done`. Two-child AST node
(condition, body) is enough because both pieces are command lists.
Newlines between the keyword tokens and their attached lists are
consumed by skip_newlines so multi-line idiomatic Bash works without
modification.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
expect TOKEN_WHILE, skip_newlines. Parse condition list. skip_newlines,
expect TOKEN_DO, skip_newlines. Parse body list. skip_newlines, expect
TOKEN_DONE. Create AST_WHILE_STATEMENT, add condition and body as
children. Return the node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_while_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse while-do-done statement

    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_WHILE from Lexer

    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Let condition be proc parse_list from parser

    proc skip_newlines from parser
    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_DO from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Let body be proc parse_list from parser

    proc skip_newlines from parser
    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_DONE from Lexer

    Let while_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_WHILE_STATEMENT
    proc add_child with while_node, condition
    proc add_child with while_node, body

    Return while_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Until-loop is the negated-condition dual of while: `until COND; do BODY;
done` runs the body while the condition is false. Same two-child shape
as while; the only difference is the AST node kind, which downstream
translation uses to flip the predicate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
expect TOKEN_UNTIL, skip_newlines, parse condition, skip_newlines,
expect TOKEN_DO, skip_newlines, parse body, skip_newlines, expect
TOKEN_DONE. Create AST_UNTIL_STATEMENT with condition and body as
children. Return node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_until_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse until-do-done statement

    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_UNTIL from Lexer

    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Let condition be proc parse_list from parser

    proc skip_newlines from parser
    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_DO from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Let body be proc parse_list from parser

    proc skip_newlines from parser
    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_DONE from Lexer

    Let until_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_UNTIL_STATEMENT
    proc add_child with until_node, condition
    proc add_child with until_node, body

    Return until_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
For-loop is `for VAR in WORD...; do BODY; done`. The iteration variable
goes into the AST_FOR_STATEMENT.value field while the word list and the
body are children. This shape lets translation walk the children to
generate iteration over the value list followed by the body, with the
loop variable name available without traversing children.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
expect TOKEN_FOR, skip_newlines. Read current token value as var_name,
expect TOKEN_WORD. skip_newlines, expect TOKEN_IN, skip_newlines. Create
AST_FOR_STATEMENT, set its value to var_name. Word-list loop: read
token type each iteration; break on TOKEN_NEWLINE, TOKEN_SEMICOLON, or
TOKEN_DO; otherwise parse_word and add as child (break if it returns 0).
After the loop, skip_newlines, optional match_and_advance on
TOKEN_SEMICOLON, skip_newlines, expect TOKEN_DO, skip_newlines, parse
body list, skip_newlines, expect TOKEN_DONE. Add body as final child.
Return for_node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_for_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse for-do-done statement

    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_FOR from Lexer

    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Let var_name be proc current_token_value from parser
    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_WORD from Lexer

    proc skip_newlines from parser
    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_IN from Lexer

    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Let for_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_FOR_STATEMENT
    proc set_node_value with for_node, var_name

    Note: Parse word list
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DO from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        Let word be proc parse_word from parser

        If word is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc add_child with for_node, word
    End While

    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Let is_semi be proc match_and_advance with parser, TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines from parser

    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_DO from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Let body be proc parse_list from parser

    proc skip_newlines from parser
    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_DONE from Lexer

    proc add_child with for_node, body

    Return for_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A case item is `PATTERN [| PATTERN ...]) COMMANDS [;;|;&|;;&]`. Patterns
can be alternated with `|`, and the trailing separator selects
fall-through behavior (`;;` stop, `;&` fall through unconditionally,
`;;&` continue testing patterns). All patterns plus the commands become
children of the AST_CASE_ITEM; the fall-through behavior is currently
discarded after the advance (downstream uses default `;;` semantics).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Create AST_CASE_ITEM. Pattern loop: parse_word; break if 0; add as
child; match_and_advance TOKEN_PIPE; break if no pipe. expect
TOKEN_RPAREN, skip_newlines. Parse commands list, add as final child.
skip_newlines. Then test the current token type for any of
TOKEN_SEMICOLON_SEMICOLON, TOKEN_SEMICOLON_SEMICOLON_AMP, or
TOKEN_SEMICOLON_AMP and advance past it if matched. Return the item
node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_case_item" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse case pattern item

    Let item_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_CASE_ITEM

    Note: Parse patterns
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let pattern be proc parse_word from parser

        If pattern is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc add_child with item_node, pattern

        Let is_pipe be proc match_and_advance with parser, TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer

        If is_pipe is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Note: Parse commands
    Let commands be proc parse_list from parser

    proc add_child with item_node, commands

    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Note: Expect ;; or ;;& or ;&
    Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
        proc advance from parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON_SEMICOLON_AMP from Lexer:
        proc advance from parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON_AMP from Lexer:
        proc advance from parser
    End If

    Return item_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Case grammar is `case WORD in ITEM... esac`. The discriminant word is
the first child; subsequent children are AST_CASE_ITEM nodes, one per
pattern arm. Newlines are permitted freely between items so multi-line
case bodies parse without modification.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
expect TOKEN_CASE, skip_newlines, parse_word as the discriminant.
skip_newlines, expect TOKEN_IN, skip_newlines. Create AST_CASE_STATEMENT
and add the discriminant. Item loop: read token type; break on
TOKEN_ESAC; parse_case_item; break if 0; add as child; skip_newlines.
After the loop, expect TOKEN_ESAC. Return the case node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_case_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse case-in-esac statement

    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_CASE from Lexer

    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Let word be proc parse_word from parser

    proc skip_newlines from parser
    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_IN from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Let case_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_CASE_STATEMENT
    proc add_child with case_node, word

    Note: Parse case items
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ESAC from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        Let item be proc parse_case_item from parser

        If item is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc add_child with case_node, item
        proc skip_newlines from parser
    End While

    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_ESAC from Lexer

    Return case_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Function Definition Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Bash function definitions have two surface forms: `function NAME [()]
BODY` (the `function` keyword path) and `NAME() BODY` (the
POSIX-compatible form handled by parse_command's lookahead). This
procedure handles the function-keyword path; the optional parentheses
after the name are accepted but produce no AST artifact since they have
no semantic effect.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
match_and_advance the TOKEN_FUNCTION keyword (is_function_kw is read but
not subsequently used because both forms reach here with the same shape
afterward). Read current token value as func_name, expect TOKEN_WORD.
skip_newlines. match_and_advance TOKEN_LPAREN; if 1, expect TOKEN_RPAREN
and skip_newlines (consumes the optional `()`). Parse the compound
command via parse_compound_command. Create AST_FUNCTION_DEFINITION, set
its value to func_name, add the body as the sole child. Return.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_function_definition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse function definition

    Let is_function_kw be proc match_and_advance with parser, TOKEN_FUNCTION from Lexer

    Let func_name be proc current_token_value from parser
    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_WORD from Lexer

    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Note: Optional ()
    Let is_lparen be proc match_and_advance with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer

    If is_lparen is equal to 1:
        proc expect with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer
        proc skip_newlines from parser
    End If

    Note: Function body (compound command)
    Let body be proc parse_compound_command from parser

    Let func_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_FUNCTION_DEFINITION
    proc set_node_value with func_node, func_name
    proc add_child with func_node, body

    Return func_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Compound Command Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Bash compound commands come in two forms with different semantics: `(
commands )` runs in a subshell with isolated environment, while `{
commands; }` runs in the current shell. The distinction is preserved at
the AST level by producing AST_SUBSHELL versus AST_COMPOUND_COMMAND so
downstream translation can emit the correct execution semantics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current token type. On TOKEN_LPAREN: advance, skip_newlines, parse
list, skip_newlines, expect TOKEN_RPAREN, create AST_SUBSHELL, attach
commands as child, return. On TOKEN_LBRACE: advance, skip_newlines,
parse list, skip_newlines, expect TOKEN_RBRACE, create
AST_COMPOUND_COMMAND, attach commands as child, return. Returns 0 if
neither bracket is current.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_compound_command" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse compound command { commands; } or ( commands )

    Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    Note: Subshell ( commands )
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer:
        proc advance from parser
        proc skip_newlines from parser

        Let commands be proc parse_list from parser

        proc skip_newlines from parser
        proc expect with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

        Let subshell_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_SUBSHELL
        proc add_child with subshell_node, commands

        Return subshell_node
    End If

    Note: Compound command { commands; }
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer:
        proc advance from parser
        proc skip_newlines from parser

        Set commands to proc parse_list from parser

        proc skip_newlines from parser
        proc expect with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer

        Let compound_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_COMPOUND_COMMAND
        proc add_child with compound_node, commands

        Return compound_node
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Variable Assignment Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Variable assignments take the form `name=value` and are recognized
upstream in parse_command via character-level lookahead (since the lexer
emits the name as a TOKEN_WORD). This procedure handles the parsing once
the lookahead has confirmed the shape: it captures the name, consumes
the `=`, parses a single argument as the rvalue.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read current token value as var_name, expect TOKEN_WORD. expect
TOKEN_ASSIGN. Parse the rvalue via parse_argument. Create
AST_VARIABLE_ASSIGNMENT, set its value to var_name, add the rvalue node
as the sole child. Return the assignment node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_variable_assignment" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse variable assignment var=value

    Let var_name be proc current_token_value from parser
    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_WORD from Lexer

    proc expect with parser, TOKEN_ASSIGN from Lexer

    Let value be proc parse_argument from parser

    Let assign_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_VARIABLE_ASSIGNMENT
    proc set_node_value with assign_node, var_name
    proc add_child with assign_node, value

    Return assign_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Command Parsing (Main Entry)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Central command-dispatch routine that selects the right sub-parser based
on the lookahead token. The non-trivial case is plain word-leading
input, which can be either a simple command (`cmd args`) or an
assignment (`name=value`); these share the same first token, so we
peek into the lexer's source buffer past the current word to look for
`=` before any list-separator character. This character-level lookahead
is a controlled use of lexer internals - the alternative would be a
multi-token reparseable lookahead protocol on the parser side.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
skip_newlines. Switch on current token type:
- TOKEN_IF -> parse_if_statement
- TOKEN_WHILE -> parse_while_statement
- TOKEN_UNTIL -> parse_until_statement
- TOKEN_FOR -> parse_for_statement
- TOKEN_CASE -> parse_case_statement
- TOKEN_FUNCTION -> parse_function_definition
- TOKEN_LBRACE / TOKEN_LPAREN -> parse_compound_command
- TOKEN_WORD -> reads the lexer pointer at parser offset 0, then the
  lexer's current peek_pos (offset 16), source (offset 0), and length
  (offset 8). Walks the source forward from peek_pos: skip space (32)
  and tab (9); on `=` (61) sets could_be_assignment to 1 and breaks; on
  any of newline (10), semicolon (59), `&` (38), or pipe (124) breaks
  without setting the flag; otherwise advances. If
  could_be_assignment is 1 returns parse_assignment. Falls through to
  parse_list for everything else.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
This is the one place in the parser that directly inspects raw source
bytes ahead of the token stream. The bounds invariant lookahead_pos <
length is checked on every iteration so the lookahead cannot read past
the end of the lexer's source buffer.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "parse_command" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse any command (control structure, function, simple command, etc.)

    proc skip_newlines from parser

    Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    Note: Control structures
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IF from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_if_statement from parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_WHILE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_while_statement from parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_UNTIL from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_until_statement from parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FOR from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_for_statement from parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_CASE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_case_statement from parser
    End If

    Note: Function definition
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FUNCTION from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_function_definition from parser
    End If

    Note: Compound commands
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_compound_command from parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_compound_command from parser
    End If

    Note: Check for variable assignment (word followed by =)
    Let next_token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    If next_token_type is equal to TOKEN_WORD from Lexer:
        Note: Peek ahead for assignment
        Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
        Let peek_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
        Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

        Note: Simple heuristic: if we see word then =, it's assignment
        Note: Proper lookahead for assignment detection
        Let could_be_assignment be 0
        Let lookahead_pos be peek_pos

        Note: Check for word followed by = pattern
        While lookahead_pos is less than length:
            Let lookahead_char be proc get_char_at_position from lexer with lookahead_pos

            Note: Skip whitespace
            If lookahead_char is equal to 32 or lookahead_char is equal to 9:
                Set lookahead_pos to lookahead_pos plus 1
                Continue
            End If

            Note: Check for assignment operator
            If lookahead_char is equal to 61:  Note: '=' character
                Set could_be_assignment to 1
                Break
            End If

            Note: If we hit a special character that's not '=', not assignment
            If lookahead_char is equal to 10 or lookahead_char is equal to 59 or lookahead_char is equal to 38 or lookahead_char is equal to 124:
                Break
            End If

            Set lookahead_pos to lookahead_pos plus 1
        End While

        Note: Parse as assignment if detected, otherwise as simple command
        If could_be_assignment is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_assignment from parser
        End If

    End If

    Note: Simple command or list
    Return proc parse_list from parser
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Script Parsing (Top-Level)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The top-level production: a script is a sequence of commands separated
by newlines, terminated by EOF. AST_SCRIPT becomes the unique tree
root. Stopping on the first 0 from parse_command lets malformed input
be partially parsed up to the failure point rather than aborting the
whole tree.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Create AST_SCRIPT root. skip_newlines. Loop: read current_token_type;
break on TOKEN_EOF; parse_command; break if 0; add command as child;
skip_newlines. Return the script node when the loop exits.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_script" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse complete Bash script

    Let script_node be proc create_ast_node from AST_SCRIPT

    proc skip_newlines from parser

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        Let command be proc parse_command from parser

        If command is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc add_child with script_node, command

        proc skip_newlines from parser
    End While

    Return script_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public entry point that lets callers reach the parser via a name
("parse") that matches the import-side dispatcher convention used by
other Bash translation modules. Pure delegation to parse_script keeps
the entry name stable even if internal structure later changes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns the result of parse_script(parser) directly. No additional
setup or teardown - the caller is responsible for parser lifetime
(create_parser before, destroy_parser after).
@End Implementation
Process called "parse" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Main parsing entry point

    Return proc parse_script from parser
End Process

Note: End of Bash Parser
